==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈreʧ:an/}}

===Etymology 1===
From Germanic *''rakjan''.  Cognate with Gothic [[𐌿𐍆𐍂𐌰𐌺𐌾𐌰𐌽]], Old Saxon [[rekkian]], Old High German [[recchan]], Old Norse [[rekja]].

====Verb====
'''reċċan''' (class 1 weak: ''3 singular present'' '''[[receþ|reċeþ]]''', ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[recede|reċede]]''', ''preterite plural'' '''[[recedon|reċedon]]''', ''past participle'' (ġe)'''[[reced|reċed]]''')

# to [[stretch]] out, [[extend]]
# to [[reach out]] to someone

===Etymology 2===
From Germanic ''*rokjan''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[rokjan]], Old High German [[ruohhen]], Old Norse [[rœkja]].

====Verb====
'''reċċan''' (class 1 weak: ''3 singular present'' '''[[receþ|reċeþ]]''', ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[rohte|rōhte]]''', ''preterite plural'' '''[[rohton|rōhton]]''', ''past participle'' (ġe)'''[[roht|rōht]]''')

# to [[care for]]
# to [[look after]]
# to take notice of, pay heed to

====Descendants====
*English: [[reck]]

